UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 479
1 (2) A pharmacist may dispense undesignated glucagon for a prescription issued in
2 the name of an authorized entity.
3 (3) A trained individual may administer undesignated glucagon in an emergency
4 situation when a school nurse or other licensed practitioner is not immediately
5 available and the trained individual believes in good faith that a student is
6 experiencing severe hypoglycemia or other conditions noted in that student's
7 diabetes medical management plan.
8 (4) An authorized entity that acquires and stocks a supply of undesignated glucagon
9 with a valid prescription shall:
10 (a) Store the undesignated glucagon in accordance with the manufacturer's
11 instructions, in a location that is immediately accessible to trained
12 individuals, and with any additional requirements established by the
13 Department for Public Health; and
14 (b) Require a school nurse or a trained individual to be responsible for the
15 storage, maintenance, and general oversight of the undesignated glucagon
16 acquired by the authorized entity.
17 (5) Any authorized entity or trained individual that acquires and stocks a supply of
18 undesignated glucagon in accordance with this section shall notify the assigned
19 school nurse or other school health care provider, an agent of the local
20 emergency medical services, and the local emergency communications or
21 dispatch center of the existence, location, and type of glucagon acquired.
22 (6) Any authorized entity or trained individual that administers or provides
23 undesignated glucagon to a student who is experiencing severe hypoglycemia or
24 other conditions noted in that student's diabetes medical management plan shall
25 contact the student's parent, guardian, or emergency contact, and local
26 emergency medical services as soon as possible.
27 (7) The requirements of subsection (6) of this section shall not apply to any
Page 2 of 4
